financial help, while eventually
reducing

10:12.979 --> 10:15.515 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the number of people on
Medicaid.

10:15.548 --> 10:17.350 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
John Yang picks it up from
there.

10:17.383 --> 10:21.221 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: To help break down
the impact of
these proposed changes, I'm
joined by two

10:21.254 --> 10:23.656 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
experts who watch health care
closely.

10:23.690 --> 10:29.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Lanhee Chen is a fellow at the
Hoover Institution
who advised Mitt Romney and
Marco Rubio in

10:29.562 --> 10:31.397 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their presidential campaigns.

10:31.431 --> 10:36.803 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And Sabrina Corlette is a
professor at Georgetown
University's Health Care Policy
Institute.

10:36.836 --> 10:38.471 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Thank you for joining us to you
both.

10:38.505 --> 10:40.306 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to you both.

10:40.340 --> 10:43.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think you can both agree that,
as this moves
through the legislative process,
the details

10:43.543 --> 10:49.949 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will change, but I think the
philosophical
changes in direction are clear
now.

10:49.983 --> 10:51.885 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Lanhee Chen, let me start with
you.

10:51.918 --> 10:57.924 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This shifts -- what we're seeing
proposed
is to shift from requiring that
everyone have

10:57.957 --> 11:03.696 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
insurance, to have a series of
carrots, really,
to get people to buy insurance
themselves

11:03.730 --> 11:05.131 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
on the open market.

11:05.164 --> 11:06.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Why is that the better approach?

11:06.933 --> 11:08.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LANHEE CHEN, Former Policy
Director, Mitt
Romney Campaign: Well, one of
the issues,

11:08.935 --> 11:13.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
frankly, with the Affordable
Care Act is that
you had situations where
insurance was become

11:13.106 --> 11:14.908 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
unaffordable.

11:14.941 --> 11:20.480 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In fact, if you look at 2015 as
an example,
19.2 million Americans either
could not afford

11:20.513 --> 11:24.484 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
health insurance because they
got what was
known as a hardship exemption,
or they paid

11:24.517 --> 11:28.254 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
the penalty relating to
Obamacare's individual
mandate.

11:28.288 --> 11:32.091 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So one of the things that this
tries to do
is to encourage the purchase of
insurance,

11:32.125 --> 11:35.328 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
but, as you say, to do it as an
encouragement,
rather than as a penalty.

11:35.361 --> 11:39.666 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, where a penalty does apply
is when an
individual doesn't make the
decision to acquire

11:39.699 --> 11:43.937 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
coverage and that coverage
lapses, and then
they would be subject to a
penalty to get

11:43.970 --> 11:45.338 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
back into the system.

11:45.371 --> 11:47.440 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But the approach, as you note,
is fundamentally
different.

11:47.473 --> 11:51.778 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, Lanhee, how does
this -- how
does this move premiums down?

11:51.811 --> 11:54.747 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LANHEE CHEN: Well, I think
there's a couple
of things.

11:54.781 --> 12:00.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, the idea is to
create marketplaces
that are healthier by providing
more competition

12:00.320 --> 12:02.088 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and a greater choice of plans.

12:02.121 --> 12:07.293 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, obviously, this provision
alone doesn't
do that, but the idea behind the
Republican

12:07.327 --> 12:09.228 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
approach is to move in that
direction.

12:09.262 --> 12:14.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, some of that lowering of
costs is constrained
in this piece of legislation
because it has

12:14.233 --> 12:17.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to comply with this budgetary
oddity known
as reconciliation.

12:17.904 --> 12:23.376 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, overall, the Republican
strategy is to
lower costs by expanding choice
and reducing

12:23.409 --> 12:24.978 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the number of mandates on plans.

12:25.011 --> 12:26.946 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Sabrina Corlette, is
that effective?

12:26.980 --> 12:28.748 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is that going to work?

12:28.781 --> 12:29.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE, Center on
Health Insurance
Reforms, Georgetown University:
Well, here's

12:29.949 --> 12:31.851 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
one of those things where
details really do
matter.

12:31.884 --> 12:39.192 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, I would argue that
this requirement
they have in there that is an
attempt to replace

12:39.225 --> 12:44.330 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the ACA's individual mandate
will actually
drive premiums up, because I
think more young

12:44.364 --> 12:48.601 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
people will look at that and
say, I'm not
going to face a penalty if I
don't sign up

12:48.635 --> 12:50.770 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for coverage, so I'm going to
hold off on
buying insurance.

12:50.803 --> 12:55.074 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so the only people buying
insurance will
be those who are sick.

12:55.108 --> 12:59.245 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if insurers have to just
cover sick people,
they will raise premiums, and
those will go

12:59.278 --> 13:01.080 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
up.

13:01.114 --> 13:04.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lanhee Chen, that
gets to a point
that many critics are saying,
that the federal

13:04.550 --> 13:11.758 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
help to buy for these insurance
premiums favors,
they say, the young and the
healthy over the

13:11.791 --> 13:13.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sick and the old.

13:13.359 --> 13:15.161 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What do you say to that?

13:15.194 --> 13:17.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
LANHEE CHEN: Well, I have a
tough time with
that argument, John, frankly,
because, first

13:17.797 --> 13:23.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of all, the tax credits in the
Republican
plan are based, first of all, on
age.

13:23.102 --> 13:25.338 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the primary factor on
which they're
differentiated.

13:25.371 --> 13:29.709 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Therefore, those who are older
will get more
assistance than those who are
younger.

13:29.742 --> 13:35.214 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Furthermore, the broader idea
here is to lower
the cost of plans to get more
people in.

13:35.248 --> 13:39.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It is the case in the previous
regime, under
Obamacare, that you did have
fewer people

13:39.819 --> 13:45.358 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the marketplace because
premiums were increasing,
for example, from 2015 to 2016
by an average

13:45.391 --> 13:47.193 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of 25 percent.

13:47.226 --> 13:50.596 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, the goal here, again,
lowering the cost
of plans, so that the help that
is provided

13:50.630 --> 13:52.732 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
by the government will buy more
coverage.

13:52.765 --> 13:55.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That is the idea and the concept
behind the
Republican proposal.

13:55.768 --> 14:02.742 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Sabrina Corlette,
he's correct
that the tax breaks go up with
age, but, also,

14:02.775 --> 14:09.615 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
it allows the insurance
companies to charge
much higher premiums for older
insured people.

14:09.649 --> 14:11.484 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE: Right, right.

14:11.517 --> 14:16.689 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, this bill would allow
insurance companies
to charge older people up to
five times the

14:16.723 --> 14:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
amount of a younger person.

14:18.091 --> 14:21.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But the tax credits only go up
two times.

14:21.094 --> 14:26.432 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you're essentially handing
an older person
a two-foot rope to get
themselves out of a

14:26.466 --> 14:28.101 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
10-foot hole.

14:28.134 --> 14:31.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
The other thing is that,
overall, the tax
subsidies are much less generous
than they

14:31.337 --> 14:32.805 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are under the Affordable Care
Act.

14:32.839 --> 14:34.507 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And they're not income-related.

14:34.540 --> 14:39.812 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So lower-income people get less,
relative
to their income, and many of
them will not

14:39.846 --> 14:41.714 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
be able to afford this coverage.

14:41.748 --> 14:45.785 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We don't have numbers yet from
the Congressional
Budget Office about how many
people will end

14:45.818 --> 14:47.653 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
up losing coverage.

14:47.687 --> 14:52.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we do have numbers that --
from Wall Street
analysts that estimate up to 10
million people

14:52.158 --> 14:53.993 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
will lose coverage under this
bill.

14:54.026 --> 14:57.263 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lanhee Chen, how do
you respond
to that, about the number of
people who will

14:57.296 --> 14:59.031 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
go uncovered by this?

14:59.065 --> 15:00.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LANHEE CHEN: I think there are a
couple of
things.

15:00.900 --> 15:04.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We will have to wait and see
what the Congressional
Budget Office ends up deciding
on this.

15:04.337 --> 15:08.608 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But it is the case, first of
all, that the
Republican philosophy, the
conservative philosophy

15:08.641 --> 15:12.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
has always been that you expand
access by
lowering costs.

15:12.178 --> 15:15.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it is the case that if you
are able to
get some of these regulation out
of the way

15:15.815 --> 15:19.418 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- now, granted, the House bill
doesn't actually
do a lot of that, because,
again, it has to

15:19.452 --> 15:21.954 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
comply with these arcane
budgetary rules.

15:21.988 --> 15:26.392 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But were there to be
legislation, let's say,
in phase two, as Donald Trump
says, of health

15:26.426 --> 15:30.696 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
reform that got these
regulations out of the
way, the idea would be to lower
the cost of

15:30.730 --> 15:34.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plans, to expand access, and
therefore affect
that number of uninsured.

15:34.534 --> 15:38.671 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another thing they could do,
briefly, is,
they could look at trying to
create a steeper

15:38.704 --> 15:43.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
means test on the tax credits,
such that poorer
people would benefit more than
they do under

15:43.376 --> 15:45.077 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the current proposal.

15:45.111 --> 15:49.048 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Lanhee Chen, what do
you say to
the conservatives who worry that
these tax

15:49.081 --> 15:52.018 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
credits are essentially a new
entitlement?

15:52.051 --> 15:55.354 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LANHEE CHEN: Well, I would make
a couple of
arguments.

15:55.388 --> 15:59.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First of all, we already have a
tax code that
subsidizes health care, largely
through the

15:59.158 --> 16:03.529 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
purchase of health insurance
through your
employer; 160 million Americans
take advantage

16:03.563 --> 16:05.364 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of this tax break already.

16:05.398 --> 16:09.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What Republicans are trying to
do with this
proposal is to equalize, to a
certain degree,

16:09.202 --> 16:13.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
the treatment of health
insurance purchased
individually vs. through
employers.

16:13.206 --> 16:17.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I would also say that it's
just a reality
that we have got to deal with
questions of

16:17.543 --> 16:19.278 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
coverage.

16:19.312 --> 16:22.348 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And if you don't help people who
are outside
of the employer marketplace, you
are going

16:22.381 --> 16:24.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to see even more significant
degradations
in coverage.

16:24.951 --> 16:26.986 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So this is an important step
forward in that
regard.

16:27.019 --> 16:32.058 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: And then, finally,
Sabrina Corlette,
what's your view on the changes
that are coming

16:32.091 --> 16:35.294 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in Medicaid, or would be coming
in Medicaid
if this plan is passed?

16:35.328 --> 16:38.831 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SABRINA CORLETTE: Well, this is
one thing
that I think is really important
for people

16:38.865 --> 16:44.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to know, is that this bill goes
way beyond
repealing the ACA's Medicaid
expansion.

16:44.670 --> 16:49.609 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
This really is a radical
restructuring of
a program that's been around for
50 years.

16:49.642 --> 16:54.614 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a financial lifeline for
not just low-income
families, but families who have
people with

16:54.647 --> 16:58.284 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- kids with disabilities, older
people who
need long-term care.

16:58.317 --> 17:02.755 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Close to 50 percent of births in
this country
are funded by the Medicaid
program.

17:02.788 --> 17:09.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So we are looking at potentially
cutting this
program that will affect far
beyond the people

17:09.362 --> 17:11.097 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
just that got coverage through
the ACA.

17:11.130 --> 17:13.699 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Sabrina Corlette,
Lanhee Chen,
thank you very much.

17:13.733 --> 17:17.703 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
LANHEE CHEN: Thank you.

17:17.737 --> 17:30.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Today, the
chairman of the
House Intelligence Committee
announced that

17:30.216 --> 17:35.187 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the first public hearing on the
investigation
into Russian interference in the
election

17:35.221 --> 17:37.356 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
would begin on March 20.

17:37.390 --> 17:41.994 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, Democrats in
the Senate
are calling for a special
counsel to investigate.

17:42.028 --> 17:46.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have heard recently from
Democrats on the
Senate Intelligence Committee.

17:46.265 --> 17:48.401 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Tonight, we turn to a
Republican.

17:48.434 --> 17:50.703 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He is Senator James Lankford of
Oklahoma.

17:50.736 --> 17:53.773 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Senator Lankford, thank you very
much for
being with us.

17:53.806 --> 17:57.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, the House committee has
announced when
its hearing beginnings.

17:57.310 --> 17:58.277 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
What about the Senate?

17:58.311 --> 17:59.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is the House going to go first?

17:59.345 --> 18:00.880 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

18:00.913 --> 18:02.648 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD (R), OKLAHOMA:
Well, the House
was doing an open meeting there.

18:02.682 --> 18:06.018 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have actually done hearings
for several
months now behind closed doors,
as most of

18:06.052 --> 18:08.387 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the Intelligence hearings are
held.

18:08.421 --> 18:12.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
These are dealing with highly
classified documents,
procedures, people, that remain
classified

18:12.992 --> 18:14.393 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and should remain classified.

18:14.427 --> 18:18.030 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So a lot of work will be held
behind closed
doors, quite frankly.

18:18.064 --> 18:21.267 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then we will actually bring
things out
when it's appropriate and when
we have actually

18:21.300 --> 18:23.736 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
some things to be able to
contribute to the
national conversation.

18:23.769 --> 18:25.905 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Are you
subpoenaing witnesses?

18:25.938 --> 18:27.440 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

18:27.473 --> 18:29.075 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: We are working
through the
process of getting witnesses.

18:29.108 --> 18:32.011 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm not going to say whether we
have to subpoena
any of them at this point.

18:32.044 --> 18:34.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I would say the witnesses
that we have
asked for, we have been able to
get access

18:34.780 --> 18:36.849 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to without having to do a
subpoena.

18:36.882 --> 18:38.751 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But we will work through that
process.

18:38.784 --> 18:40.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
This is very similar.

18:40.720 --> 18:43.756 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I know you will remember, in
December, President
Obama in his press conference
was asked about

18:43.789 --> 18:49.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the administration investigation
into all
this process, and he said at
that time, in

18:49.161 --> 18:52.498 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
December, the American people
are going to
be somewhat frustrated by an
investigation

18:52.531 --> 18:55.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that deals with intelligence,
because we can't
put out all the sources and
methods.

18:55.735 --> 18:59.138 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We want to still be able to
guard what we're
doing in foreign intelligence in
the days

18:59.171 --> 19:00.973 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
ahead.

19:01.007 --> 19:04.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we will put out what we can
possibly put
out, but a lot of the work will
be very quiet.

19:04.110 --> 19:09.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think it
is a good idea
to look at President Trump's tax
records in

19:09.882 --> 19:14.487 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
order to get an understanding of
his possible
business connections with
Russia?

19:14.520 --> 19:16.288 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

19:16.322 --> 19:18.524 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: So, that's been
an accusation
that has sat out there, but it
has had no

19:18.557 --> 19:20.393 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
validity.

19:20.426 --> 19:22.962 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I have yet to have anyone who
has been able
to point to anything, because
the description

19:22.995 --> 19:26.932 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
there is that he had some sort
of secret business
dealings with Russia.

19:26.966 --> 19:29.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
No one has stepped forward to be
able to actually
make that accusation.

19:29.468 --> 19:31.837 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Typically, it's people saying,
hey, we want
to go search.

19:31.871 --> 19:33.572 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We want to go look.

19:33.606 --> 19:36.142 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I know that there are people
that are
frustrated that he didn't put
his tax records

19:36.175 --> 19:37.943 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
out.

19:37.977 --> 19:39.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so I think this is kind of
their vehicle
to get it and then hopefully to
be able to

19:39.745 --> 19:43.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- once they get it in their
hands, to be
able to slip it out into the
media at some

19:43.049 --> 19:44.316 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
point and leak it out.

19:44.350 --> 19:46.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But, right now, there's no
reason to even
go do that.

19:46.852 --> 19:51.157 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there's a constitutional
issue between
the Congress reaching to a
sitting president

19:51.190 --> 19:53.392 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and requiring him to turn over
personal documents.

19:53.426 --> 19:57.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, you're
saying, at this
point, you and others, the
majority on the

19:57.563 --> 20:00.232 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
committee, assume the tax
records are not
relevant?

20:00.266 --> 20:01.901 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

20:01.934 --> 20:03.736 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: Yes, I have yet
to see anything
that would say those are
relevant.

20:03.769 --> 20:06.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, there are a lot of issues
we have got
to delve into, but I have not
seen that that's

20:06.539 --> 20:08.340 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
a relevant document for us to
get.

20:08.374 --> 20:13.879 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: President Trump,
in connection
with all this, tweeted over the
weekend that

20:13.913 --> 20:21.720 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama ordered a
wiretap of him during
the campaign in his offices in
New York.

20:21.754 --> 20:24.256 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
He suggests that he has evidence
of this.

20:24.290 --> 20:25.958 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Are you aware of any evidence of
that?

20:25.991 --> 20:27.726 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

20:27.760 --> 20:29.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: I would just say
to the White
House, if they have evidence of
that, they

20:29.528 --> 20:32.364 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can turn that over to our
committee and we
will follow that up as part of
our ongoing

20:32.398 --> 20:34.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
evaluation.

20:34.200 --> 20:35.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But that would be something the
president
should turn over to Congress as
we're walking

20:35.734 --> 20:37.536 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
through our investigation

20:37.570 --> 20:42.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you take the
president at
his word, then, that there is
indeed evidence?

20:42.108 --> 20:46.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Because -- I'm asking because
the president
has in turn called on Congress
to investigate

20:46.745 --> 20:47.713 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
this.

20:47.746 --> 20:49.582 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

20:49.615 --> 20:50.649 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: Well, it would
help, obviously,
if the White House turned those
document over,

20:50.683 --> 20:52.852 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
so we could include that into
our investigation.

20:52.885 --> 20:56.655 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're walking through a very
thorough process,
multiple different agencies in
an extremely

20:56.689 --> 20:57.990 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
bipartisan way.

20:58.023 --> 21:00.493 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Intelligence Committee is
not a partisan
committee.

21:00.526 --> 21:01.694 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We work behind closed doors.

21:01.727 --> 21:03.295 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
It's not showboating.

21:03.329 --> 21:04.830 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We're not trying to actually get
some kind
of leverage.

21:04.864 --> 21:06.398 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is a national security
issue.

21:06.432 --> 21:10.035 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is an issue we dealt
with, with Russia
for decades.

21:10.069 --> 21:13.205 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They have tried to manipulate
elections all
around the world.

21:13.239 --> 21:17.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They go back in the United
States as far as
putting a KGB person onto
President Carter's

21:17.843 --> 21:19.478 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
campaign decades ago.

21:19.512 --> 21:23.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But they have never done it so
overt and so
aggressive as they did this
time.

21:23.516 --> 21:28.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it is to our national benefit
to get this
right and to be able to have a
good investigation,

21:28.154 --> 21:30.156 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
because this is not a partisan
issue.

21:30.189 --> 21:32.892 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is a security issue for a
very long time,
and we have got to address it.

21:32.925 --> 21:36.629 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, have you
asked the White
House to turn such evidence over
to the committee?

21:36.662 --> 21:38.330 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

21:38.364 --> 21:39.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: Yes, I would say
what you
and I have just talked about
before, I have

21:39.732 --> 21:40.699 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
said plenty of places publicly.

21:40.733 --> 21:42.067 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I won't say what we have done
privately.

21:42.101 --> 21:44.003 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
How about that?

21:44.036 --> 21:47.072 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you think it
was appropriate
for President Trump to say this
without providing

21:47.106 --> 21:48.073 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that evidence?

21:48.107 --> 21:49.875 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

21:49.909 --> 21:51.277 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: I think it's
difficult to
say that, because the natural
question from

21:51.310 --> 21:54.013 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
every one of the American people
is, really,
when did that happen?

21:54.046 --> 21:55.814 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
How did that happen?

21:55.848 --> 21:57.950 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think it's something the
president is
going to have to address in the
days ahead.

21:57.983 --> 22:00.119 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But I will allow the White House
to be able
to respond to that.

22:00.152 --> 22:04.456 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Senator, there is
a new story
today you're aware of, WikiLeaks
releasing

22:04.490 --> 22:10.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
thousands of pages of these
documents which
we're only beginning, really, to
see what's

22:10.329 --> 22:17.403 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in that material, looking at
what the CIA's
methods are for hacking,
allegedly hacking,

22:17.436 --> 22:22.841 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
into everything from iPhones to
cars, televisions.

22:22.875 --> 22:25.110 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you know about that?

22:25.144 --> 22:28.280 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And how serious a security
breach could this
be?

22:28.314 --> 22:29.615 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

22:29.648 --> 22:30.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: So, let me give
you a series
of things to this.

22:30.616 --> 22:32.418 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WikiLeaks is not saying where
they got it.

22:32.451 --> 22:36.055 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are just saying that they
have this information
and that it was out there.

22:36.088 --> 22:39.525 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I would remind people there's a
tremendous
amount of fake news out there.

22:39.558 --> 22:43.829 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I'm not making an accusation
here, but there
is quite a bit out there that
people create,

22:43.862 --> 22:47.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
being able to release out and to
say this
looks genuine and so we will put
this out.

22:47.666 --> 22:51.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Quite a few of these documents
like this,
we get a chance to look at later
and find

22:51.337 --> 22:53.672 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
out they're really not genuine
after all.

22:53.706 --> 22:57.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I would caution people first
to be able
to jump to conclusions of this.

22:57.676 --> 23:02.181 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Second, when we deal with any
kind of what
is actually an intelligence
process, any time

23:02.214 --> 23:07.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anyone, WikiLeaks or anyone
else, releases
out, gets access to this, it
does two things.

23:07.853 --> 23:11.790 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It always asks the question of,
how did it
come from, where did it come
from at any point,

23:11.824 --> 23:13.492 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
if it's proved to be genuine?

23:13.525 --> 23:15.261 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That has to be corrected.

23:15.294 --> 23:20.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The second part of it is, it
means that any
adversary out there anywhere in
the world,

23:20.132 --> 23:24.670 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
whether it be any government,
whether it be
any terrorist organization
suddenly gets information.

23:24.703 --> 23:27.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That is toxic to the American
people.

23:27.806 --> 23:31.877 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The folks in the intelligence
community are
not targeting American citizens.

23:31.910 --> 23:37.216 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are very strict, clear
laws that protect
U.S. persons from anyone in the
intelligence.

23:37.249 --> 23:39.084 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But I would be very frank with
you.

23:39.118 --> 23:43.589 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We are very aggressive to try to
get information
about terrorist organizations,
foreign entities

23:43.622 --> 23:45.124 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that mean to do us harm.

23:45.157 --> 23:46.959 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And I'm glad that we do.

23:46.992 --> 23:50.896 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If someone means to do harm to
the United
States, to any United States
citizen, we should

23:50.929 --> 23:54.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
try to find out first, rather
than react to
it after the fact.

23:54.300 --> 23:58.437 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And people who try to release
out any methods
that are out there are damaging
the national

23:58.470 --> 24:00.406 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
security of the United States.

24:00.439 --> 24:07.680 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Senator James
Lankford, Republican
on the Senate Intelligence
Committee, we thank

24:07.713 --> 24:08.814 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you.

24:08.847 --> 24:09.948 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

24:09.982 --> 24:14.520 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JAMES LANKFORD: Thank you.

24:14.553 --> 24:20.392 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: As we just
discussed, WikiLeaks
today did publish thousands of
pages of what

24:20.426 --> 24:24.863 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it says are files about the CIA
and its hacking
activities.

24:24.897 --> 24:26.565 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Brown has our further
look.

24:26.598 --> 24:30.703 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: The material
comes from the
CIA's Center for Cyber
Intelligence.

24:30.736 --> 24:36.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It includes a range of documents
from 2013
to 2016 which describe
cyber-tools for hacking

24:36.308 --> 24:39.845 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
cell phones, computers,
television, and even
vehicles.

24:39.878 --> 24:42.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The documents also contain
computer code.

24:42.815 --> 24:48.620 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One program, dubbed Weeping
Angel, entails
infecting Samsung smart TVs,
turning them

24:48.654 --> 24:50.489 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
into bugging devices.

24:50.522 --> 24:55.127 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Another program is aimed at
hacking Apple
and Android cell phones,
undercutting encryption

24:55.160 --> 24:59.064 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
on services like WhatsApp,
Signal, and Telegram.

24:59.098 --> 25:03.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WikiLeaks also says these
documents show that
when the CIA discovered flaws in
computer

25:03.936 --> 25:09.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
code written by Apple, Google or
Samsung,
it failed to notify those
companies about

25:09.541 --> 25:13.045 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the vulnerabilities to allow
fixes to be made.

25:13.078 --> 25:16.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Mark Mazzetti of The New York
Times has been
covering this, and joins us now.

25:16.915 --> 25:17.883 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Mark, welcome to you.

25:17.916 --> 25:20.319 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, the CIA hasn't said much so
far.

25:20.352 --> 25:25.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What do we know about the
authenticity of
the documents and where they
came from?

25:25.057 --> 25:29.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK MAZZETTI, The New York
Times: Well, we're
still trying to confirm the
authenticity.

25:29.361 --> 25:34.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have several people we have
spoken to today
who say they believe they're
authentic.

25:34.066 --> 25:39.805 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have heard nothing thus far
from the government
indicating that they are not.

25:39.838 --> 25:44.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Some people we have spoken to
have said that
some of the code names that were
cited in

25:44.209 --> 25:46.912 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the documents are, indeed,
legitimate.

25:46.945 --> 25:52.084 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it does appear at the moment
-- and I should
say at the moment -- that they
are legitimate.

25:52.117 --> 25:57.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Well, when you
look at the
totality, Mark, of all of these
cyber-tools

25:57.389 --> 26:01.693 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that being described, help us
understand,
what are they aimed at?

26:01.727 --> 26:03.495 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What is this program about?

26:03.529 --> 26:08.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK MAZZETTI: Well, they're a
series of -- and
we're talking about thousands of
documents

26:08.167 --> 26:15.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that are laying out some of the
tools the
CIA allegedly has to carry out
hacking of

26:15.073 --> 26:24.716 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
any number of different devices,
as you said,
cars, against foreign
adversaries or people

26:24.750 --> 26:26.485 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
overseas.

26:26.518 --> 26:33.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I should stress that there is --
unlike the
Snowden disclosures, there were
not specific

26:33.659 --> 26:36.462 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
mentions of where these have
been used.

26:36.495 --> 26:39.865 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But they're more sort of like
the toolkit
the CIA has.

26:39.898 --> 26:44.937 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And it's pretty expansive, if
the documents
are to be believed.

26:44.970 --> 26:47.806 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in terms of where they came
from, you
asked.

26:47.840 --> 26:50.442 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, that's another thing
we're still trying
to figure out.

26:50.476 --> 26:56.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WikiLeaks said today that they
had a source
come to them who was concerned
about the use

26:56.815 --> 26:58.884 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of these tools.

26:58.917 --> 27:01.487 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We don't know anything about the
source.

27:01.520 --> 27:03.288 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And there's a lot of questions
still at the
moment.

27:03.322 --> 27:09.361 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: WikiLeaks said
that it had
redacted some names and some
information in

27:09.394 --> 27:10.462 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
its release.

27:10.496 --> 27:14.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But how potentially damaging is
this to the
CIA?

27:14.199 --> 27:23.275 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARK MAZZETTI: Well, again, if
they're confirmed
to be true, any revelations
about actual capabilities

27:23.308 --> 27:29.781 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that the CIA or any other
intelligence agency
has would limit the ability of
the agency

27:29.815 --> 27:33.252 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to continue to do those
activities.

27:33.285 --> 27:38.190 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You saw that to a degree with
Snowden and
others.

27:38.223 --> 27:44.062 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so that is where the concern
is, that
you will have a lot of -- these
tools may

27:44.096 --> 27:46.832 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
not be used because they're now
revealed.

27:46.865 --> 27:52.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, again, we have to -- we
still have to
report out exactly, you know,
what has been

27:52.538 --> 27:57.676 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
used and, to a large extent, how
much of this
is actual truth.

27:57.709 --> 27:59.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JEFFREY BROWN: Yes, and I
realize so much
of that is going on.

27:59.778 --> 28:05.050 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
