day care no
later than 5:30.

31:33.258 --> 31:36.795 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Staff Sergeant
Kathleen Hargrove
is a single mother.

31:36.828 --> 31:38.363 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
STAFF SGT.

31:38.396 --> 31:39.965 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
KATHLEEN HARGROVE: I can't
really use excuses
to be late in the Marine Corps.

31:39.998 --> 31:43.034 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's not an acceptable answer.

31:43.068 --> 31:45.504 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They expect you to be there when
you're told
to be.

31:45.537 --> 31:49.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KAVITHA CARDOZA: Across all
branches of service,
members of the U.S. military
have about two

31:50.008 --> 31:54.846 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
million children, more than 40
percent of
them under the age of 5.

31:54.880 --> 31:58.583 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But child care in the military
hasn't always
been this good.

31:58.617 --> 32:02.120 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DEBORAH PHILLIPS, Georgetown
University: In
the '70s, the military child
care system was

32:02.154 --> 32:05.123 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
